🔧 1. Create a Git Repository
👉 Option A: Local Repository
Bash

mkdir my-project
cd my-project
git init
👉 Option B: GitHub Repository
Go to GitHub

Click New Repository

Name it (e.g., my-project)

Click Create

📥 2. Clone Repository
Bash

git clone https://github.com/username/my-project.git
cd my-project
👉 This copies the remote repo to your local system.

✏️ 3. Add & Commit Changes
Step 1: Create/Edit a file
Bash

echo "Hello World" > file.txt
Step 2: Add file to staging
Bash

git add file.txt
Step 3: Commit changes
Bash

git commit -m "Initial commit"
🚀 4. Push to Remote Repository
Bash

git push origin main
👉 Uploads your local commits to GitHub.

🔄 5. Fetch Changes
Bash

git fetch origin
👉 Gets updates from remote but does NOT merge.

🔃 6. Pull Changes
Bash

git pull origin main
👉 Fetch + Merge (updates your local repo).

🌿 7. Checkout (Switch Branches)
Create new branch
Bash

git branch feature-branch
Switch branch
Bash

git checkout feature-branch
👉 Or directly:

Bash

git checkout -b feature-branch
⏪ 8. Reset (Undo Changes)
Soft Reset (keeps changes)
Bash

git reset --soft HEAD~1
Hard Reset (deletes changes)
Bash

git reset --hard HEAD~1
👉 Use carefully ⚠️

❌ 9. Delete
Delete file
Bash

git rm file.txt
git commit -m "Deleted file"
Delete branch
Bash

git branch -d feature-branch
Delete remote branch
Bash

git push origin --delete feature-branch
📊 Summary Table
Command	Purpose
git clone	Copy repo
git add	Stage files
git commit	Save changes
git push	Upload changes
git fetch	Get updates
git pull	Fetch + merge
git checkout	Switch branches
git reset	Undo changes
git rm	Delete files

✅ Mini Workflow Example
Bash

git clone https://github.com/user/repo.git
cd repo
echo "New line" >> file.txt
git add .
git commit -m "Updated file"
git push origin main
